Previously, we demonstrated in [31] that the position and intensity of fluorescence band depend on its excitation wavelength (λexc
                     ) both for non-doped and S,N-doped CDs. The most intense luminescence was registered for λex

                     c = 350 nm. Under these conditions, the maximum of the fluorescence spectrum falls at 430 nm for both types of CDs (SI, Fig. S3). The lifetime of the CDs 1:2 fluorescence  in aqueous solutions was equal to 9.2 ± 0.2 ns and 6.6 ± 0.2 ns for CDs 1:0.

Thus, the data obtained indicate that the photoexcitation of solutions lead to the formation of CDs triplets (T) as a result of the singlet–triplet intersystem crossing. The formed triplets of CDs decay through the direct intersystem radiative transition – phosphorescence (hυPhos
                     ) and through reverse intersystem crossing from triplet (T) to excited singlet (S1
                     ) state with consequence emission of hυTADF
                     . In addition, during the lifetime of the triplet state of CDs the formation of collision complexes 

                           [
                           T
                           ·
                           ·
                           ·
                           T
                           ]

                      occurs that are consist of two triplets of CDs. These complexes decay with the emission of an ADF photon (hυADF
                     ).

It should be expected that a larger number of triplet-excited particles will lead to more efficient sensitization of singlet oxygen O2(
1
Δ g
) (Fig. 3b). As can be seen from the data obtained, the phosphorescence lifetime (τ Δ) of O2(
1
Δ g
) also increases with an growth in the part of alcohol in the solution, since the concentration of oxygen and τ Δ of O2(1Δg) in ethanol is higher than in water [16,17]. The values of τrise , as a rule, correlate with the lifetime of the triplet state of the sensitizer in air-saturated solutions [43]. However, in our experiments, we were unable to register the CDs phosphorescence signal at atmospheric pressure with sufficient reliability due to its strong quenching by oxygen and scattered light from water. The kinetics of the phosphorescence rise of O2(
1
Δ g
) with τrise also cannot be determined with high accuracy, because the signal of instrumental response function (IRF, ∼1 µs) is overlaps on the measured signal.

The efficiency of singlet oxygen sensitization can be increased in the presence of plasmonic NPs. We have studied the effect of gold NPs on the optical properties of a solution of CDs with 75 vol% of ethanol (Fig. 5
                     ). In the presence of plasmonic NPs, no change in the shape of the absorption or fluorescence specrum of CDs was recorded (Fig. 5a). The absorptivity of CDs is practically independent of the addition of gold NPs to the solution. While under the same conditions, the fluorescence intensity (Ifl
                     ) was increased by 11 – 27 %. The maximum growth in Ifl
                      was obtained at a concentration of CAu
                      = 10-13 mol/L. The lifetime of fast fluorescence was changed insignificantly.
